ce:section.ce:para:
Electrochemical energy devices with GNCO as an electrode material have good capacitive performance. NiCo2O4 exhibits the parent spinel structure in which Ni atoms are located at octahedral sites and Co atoms are distributed at tetrahedral and octahedral sites [22,41,42]. The rich redox electrochemistry is associated with the distribution of two cations among tetrahedral and octahedral sites and related redox reactions Ni2+/Ni3+ and Co2+/Co3+. Thus, in situ XAS was utilized to examine changes in the local and electronic structures in NCO and GNCO samples during the charge/discharge process under applied potentials in the order 0.0 V, +0.25 V, +0.5 V, +0.25 V (r0.25 V), 0.0 V (r0.0 V), as indicated in Fig. 7
                     . The energy of the absorption edge in the Co K-edge spectra does not significantly shift when a potential is applied, revealing that no obvious electrochemical activity at Co sites in either NCO or GNCO2. In contrast, the absorption edge in the Ni K-edge XAS spectra gradually shifted to higher energy and lost intensity during charging from 0.0 V to 0.5 V, as a result of changes in the oxidation state of Ni. During the discharge process, the absorption edge shifted to lower energy, suggesting that the oxidation state of Ni was reduced to its initial state. Additionally, the energy shift of absorption edge in GNCO2 during the charge/discharge process is greater than that in NCO, as shown in the inset in Fig. 7(b). These results reveal that GNCO2 has more Ni active sites than NCO. To understand better the enhancement of the electrochemical activity of NiCo2O4 upon modification with GQDs, ex situ XAS analyses of NCO and GNCO2 at the O K-edge (Fig. 8
                     ) and the C K-edge (Fig. 9
                     ) were conducted at various states-of-charge. The intensities of the A8 and B8 features in the O K-edge depend strongly on the number of Ni/Co itinerant 3d holes in the ligand-metal bond as a result of the strongly mixed Ni/Co 3d and O 2p character. Variations in the A8/B8 ratio in GNCO2 are reversible, indicating the high degree of reversibility of its electronic structure during the charge/discharge process. Unlike GNCO2, NCO exhibited no obvious change of A8/B8 intensity. Fig. 9 compares the C K-edge ex situ XAS spectra of GNCO2 electrodes in the charge/discharge process. The inset in Fig. 9 shows the region that includes features A9 and C9. During the charging process, the intensities of features A9 and C9 increase; during discharge, these features return to their initial states, indicating the decent reversibility of the charge compensation process. These results reflect the fact that oxygen-containing functional groups on the surface of GNCO2 can be reversibly transformed through Faradaic reactions that proceed close to the material surface as a result of the formation of strong oxygen-carbon bridges, which further promote metal-to-ligand charge-transfer at the interface between NiCo2O4 and GQDs. Hence, GNCO2 is expected to provide rich active sites, improving its electrochemical properties. These results provide evidence that GNCO2 has greatly enhanced electrochemical and capacitive characteristics as a result of the combination of both double-layer capacitive and pseudo-capacitive contributions. Fig. 10
                      illustrates the different energy storage/conversion mechanisms of NCO and GNCO. The different capacitive performances of NCO and GNCO are attributed to the following. First, the intensities of the C (K-edge), O (K-edge), Ni, and Co (L-edge) change upon the introduction of GQDs into NiCo2O4: the intensities of the C K-edge (feature A3) and Ni/Co L-edge XAS decrease while the pre-edge feature intensity in the O K-edge XAS increases, reflecting a strong CONi/Co interaction at the interface between NiCo2O4 and GQDs, which thus has many exposed active sites. Second, the strong CONi/Co interaction provides highly conductive channels as effective electron/ion paths, accelerating transport and further improving electrochemical performance. Third, the strong CONi/Co interaction changes the electronic properties, which can be monitored by in/ex situ XAS techniques. In/ex situ XAS reveals the reversibility of the local structural and oxidation state changes (especially the Ni active sites in GNCO), which explains the greater contribution of Ni2+/Ni3+ and Co2+/Co3+ redox-related pseudo-capacitance during the charge/discharge process that was observed for GNCO with highly active sites.
